<exercisegroup><introduction><conceptual/></introduction>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>R</m> be the square
<md>
<mrow>
R=\Set{(x,y)}{0\le x\le 1,\ 0\le y\le 1}
</mrow>
</md>
and let <m>f(x,y)</m> have continuous first partial derivatives.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Use the fundamental theorem of calculus to show that
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_R\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
=\int_0^1 f(x,1)\ \dee{x}
  - \int_0^1 f(x,0)\ \dee{x}
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
<li>
Use Green's theorem to show that
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_R\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
=\int_0^1 f(x,1)\ \dee{x}
  - \int_0^1 f(x,0)\ \dee{x}
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)
Expressing the left hand side as an iterated integral,
with <m>y</m> as the inner integration variable, we have
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_R\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\left[\int_0^1\dee{y}\
                \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\ \big[f(x,1)-f(x,0)\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in\text{by the fundamental theorem of calculus}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^1 f(x,1)\ \dee{x} - \int_0^1 f(x,0)\ \dee{x}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b)
Define <m>F_1(x,y)=f(x,y)</m> and <m>F_2(x,y)=0</m>. Then. by Green's theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_R\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
&amp;=-\dblInt_R\Big[\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}(x,y)
                -\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}(x,y)\Big]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_{\partial R}\big[F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x} +F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_{\partial R}f(x,y)\,\dee{x}
</mrow>
</md>
The boundary of <m>R</m>, oriented counterclockwise, is the union of four
line segments.
</p>

<sidebyside widths="45% 30%" valign="middle">
<p>
  <md>
  <mrow>C_1 \text{ from } (0,0) \text{ to } (1,0)</mrow>
  <mrow>C_2 \text{ from } (1,0) \text{ to } (1,1)</mrow>
  <mrow>C_3 \text{ from } (1,1) \text{ to } (0,1)</mrow>
  <mrow>C_4 \text{ from } (0,1) \text{ to } (0,0)</mrow>
  </md>
</p>
<image source="pfigs/domainSquare"/>
</sidebyside>


<p>
Now <m>x</m> is constant on <m>C_2</m> and <m>C_4</m> so that
<me>
\int_{C_2}f(x,y)\,\dee{x} = \int_{C_4}f(x,y)\,\dee{x} =0
</me>
So, using <m>-C_3</m> to denote the line segment from <m>(0,1)</m> to <m>(1,1)</m>
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_R\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}(x,y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
&amp;=-\left[\int_{C_1}f(x,y)\,\dee{x}+\int_{C_3}f(x,y)\,\dee{x}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_{-C_3}f(x,y)\,\dee{x}-\int_{C_1}f(x,y)\,\dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^1 f(x,1)\ \dee{x}  - \int_0^1 f(x,0)\ \dee{x}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
 Let <m>R</m> be a finite region in the <m>xy</m>-plane,
whose boundary, <m>C</m>, consists of a single, piecewise smooth, simple
closed curve that is oriented counterclockwise.
<q>Simple</q> means that the curve does not intersect itself.
Use Green's theorem to show that
<me>
\dblInt_R\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}=\oint_C\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{s}
</me>
where <m>\vF=F_1\,\hi+F_2\,\hj</m>, <m>\hn</m> is the outward unit normal to <m>C</m> and <m>s</m>
is the arclength along <m>C</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="45%">
<image source="pfigs/GreenDiv"/>
</sidebyside>
</statement>

<hint><p>
Let <m>\vr(s)=x(s)\,\hi+y(s)\,\hj</m> be a counterclockwise parametrization of
<m>C</m> by arc length. Then <m>\hT(s) = \vr'(s) = x'(s)\,\hi+y'(s)\,\hj</m>
is the forward pointing unit tangent vector to <m>C</m> at <m>\vr(s)</m>
and <m>\hn(s) = \vr'(s)\times\hk=y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj</m>. To see
that <m>\vr'(s)\times\hk</m> really is <m>\hn(s)</m>, note that
<m>y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj</m>
<ul>
<li>
has the same length, namely <m>1</m>, as <m>\vr'(s)</m> (recall that <m>\vr(s)</m> is a
parametrization by arc length),
</li>
<li>
lies in the <m>xy</m>-plane and
</li>
<li>
is perpendicular to <m>\vr'(s)</m>.
(Check that <m>\vr'(s)\cdot\big[y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj\big]=0</m>.)
</li>
<li>
Use the right hand rule to check that <m>\vr'(s)\times\hk</m> is
<m>\hn</m> rather than <m>-\hn</m>.
</li>
</ul>
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let <m>\vr(s)=x(s)\,\hi+y(s)\,\hj</m> be a counterclockwise parametrization of
<m>C</m> by arc length. Then <m>\hT(s) = \vr'(s) = x'(s)\,\hi+y'(s)\,\hj</m>
is the forward pointing unit tangent vector to <m>C</m> at <m>\vr(s)</m>
and <m>\hn(s) = \vr'(s)\times\hk=y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj</m>. To see
that <m>\vr'(s)\times\hk</m> really is <m>\hn(s)</m>, note that
<m>y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj</m>
<ul>
<li>
has the same length, namely <m>1</m>, as <m>\vr'(s)</m> (recall that <m>\vr(s)</m> is a
parametrization by arc length),
</li>
<li>
lies in the <m>xy</m>-plane and
</li>
<li>
is perpendicular to <m>\vr'(s)</m>.
(Check that <m>\vr'(s)\cdot\big[y'(s)\,\hi-x'(s)\,\hj\big]=0</m>.)
</li>
<li>
Use the right hand rule to check that <m>\vr'(s)\times\hk</m> is
<m>\hn</m> rather than <m>-\hn</m>.
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<sidebyside width="35%">
<image source="pfigs/GreenDivB"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So, by Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot\hn\,\dee{s}
&amp;=\oint_C\left[F_1\,\diff{y}{s}-F_2\,\diff{x}{s}\right]\,\dee{s}
=\oint_C\left[-F_2\,\dee{x}+F_1\,\dee{y}\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_R\left[\pdiff{}{x}F_1-\pdiff{}{y}(-F_2)\right]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_R\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="prb_Green_singular">
<statement><p>
Integrate <m>\ds\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_C \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}</m>
counterclockwise around
<ol marker="a">
<li> the circle <m>x^2+y^2=a^2</m>
</li>
<li> the boundary of the square with vertices
         <m>(-1,-1)</m>, <m>(-1,1)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>(1,-1)</m>
</li>
<li> the boundary of the region <m>1\le x^2+y^2\le 2,\ y\ge0</m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Use direct evaluation!
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>1</m> </p><p>
(b) <m>1</m> </p><p>
(c) <m>0</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Parametrize the circle by
<m>x=a\cos\theta,\ y=a\sin\theta</m>, <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>. Then
<m>\dee{x}=-a\sin\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m> and
<m>\dee{y}=a\cos\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m> so that
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_C \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
&amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{a^2\cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}+a^2\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}}
             {a^2\cos^2\theta+a^2\sin^2\theta}
=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=1
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) The boundary of the square has four sides <mdash/> one
with <m>y=-1</m>, one with <m>x=1</m>, one with <m>y=1</m> and one with <m>x=-1</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="40%">
<image source="pfigs/singGnA"/>
</sidebyside>
<p>
To evaluate the integrals over the four sides
<ul>
<li>
parametrize the <m>y=-1</m> part by <m>x</m> so that
<m>\vr(x)  = x\,\hi-\hj</m>, <m>\vr'(x)=\hi</m>, with <m>x</m> running from <m>-1</m> to <m>1</m>,
</li>
<li>
parametrize the <m>x=+1</m> part by <m>y</m> so that
<m>\vr(y)  = \hi+y\,\hj</m>, <m>\vr'(y)=\hj</m>, with <m>y</m> running from <m>-1</m> to <m>1</m>,
</li>
<li>
parametrize the <m>y=+1</m> part by <m>x</m> so that
<m>\vr(x)  = x\,\hi+\hj</m>, <m>\vr'(x)=\hi</m>, with <m>x</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>, and
</li>
<li>
parametrize the <m>x=-1</m> part by <m>y</m> so that
<m>\vr(y)  = -\hi+y\,\hj</m>, <m>\vr'(y)=\hj</m>, with <m>y</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>-1</m>,
</li>
</ul>
so that the integral
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_C \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
&amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\overbrace{\int_{-1}^1 \frac{-(-1)\dee{x}}{x^2+1}}^{y=-1{\rm\ part}}
+\frac{1}{2\pi}\overbrace{\int_{-1}^1 \frac{(1)\dee{y}}{1+y^2}}^{x=+1{\rm\ part}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in
+\frac{1}{2\pi}\overbrace{\int^{-1}_1 \frac{-(1)\dee{x}}{x^2+1}}^{y=+1{\rm\ part}}
+\frac{1}{2\pi}\overbrace{\int^{-1}_1 \frac{(-1)\dee{y}}{1+y^2}}^{x=-1{\rm\ part}}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=4\frac{1}{2\pi}\arctan x\bigg|_{-1}^1
=\frac{2}{\pi}\Big[\frac{\pi}{4}+\frac{\pi}{4}\Big]
=1
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(c)
As in part (a) with <m>a=\sqrt{2}</m>, but with <m>\theta</m> running from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi</m>,
the outer semicircle gives
<me>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{\pi} \frac{a^2\cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}+a^2\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}}
             {a^2\cos^2\theta+a^2\sin^2\theta}
=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_0^{\pi}\dee{\theta}
=\frac{1}{2}
</me>
</p>

<sidebyside width="55%">
<image source="pfigs/singGnB"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
As in part (a) with <m>a=1</m>, but with <m>\theta</m> running from <m>\pi</m> to <m>0</m>,
the inner semicircle
gives
<me>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\int^0_{\pi} \frac{a^2\cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}+a^2\sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}}
             {a^2\cos^2\theta+a^2\sin^2\theta}
=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int^0_{\pi}\dee{\theta}
=-\frac{1}{2}
</me>
The two flat pieces each give zero, since
on them <m>y=0</m> and <m>\dee{y}=0</m>. So
<me>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_C \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
=\frac{1}{2}+0-\frac{1}{2}+0=0
</me>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Show that
<md>
<mrow>
\pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
=\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
</mrow>
</md>
for all <m>(x,y)\ne (0,0)</m>. Discuss the connection between this result and
the results of Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>].
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The functions <m>\frac{x}{x^2+y^2}</m>
and <m>\frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}</m> are not defined, let alone continuous or
differentiable, at <m>x=y=0</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
See the solution.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The two partial derivatives
<md alignment="alignat">
<mrow>
\pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
&amp;=\ \ \frac{(x^2+y^2)-x(2x)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
&amp;&amp;=\frac{y^2-x^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
</mrow><mrow>
\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
&amp;=\frac{-(x^2+y^2)-(-y)(2y)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
&amp;&amp;=\frac{y^2-x^2}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
</mrow>
</md>
are well-defined and equal everywhere except at the origin <m>(0,0)</m>.
</p>

<p><em>Short discussion:</em>
Were it not for the singularity at <m>(0,0)</m>, the vector field of the last
problem would be conservative and the integral <m>\int\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>
around any closed curve would be zero. But as we saw in parts (a) and (b) of
Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>], this is not the case. On the other hand,
by Green's theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
the integral around the boundary of any region that
does not contain <m>(0,0)</m> is zero, as happened in part (c) of
Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>].
</p>

<p><em>Long discussion:</em> First consider part (c) of
Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>]. The curve <m>C</m> is the boundary of
the region
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{1\le x^2+y^2\le 2,\ y\ge 0}
</me>
The partial derivatives
<m>\pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)</m>
and
<m>\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)</m>
are well-defined and equal everywhere in <m>R</m>. So by Green's
theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_C \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
&amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\dblInt_R\left[
   \pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
 -\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)\right]\dee{x}\, \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
which is the answer we got before.
</p>

<p>We cannot apply Green's theorem
in this way for parts (a) and (b) of Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>] because
the singularity at <m>(0,0)</m> is inside the curve <m>C</m> for both parts
(a) and (b). On the other hand suppose, for simplicity, that <m>0 \lt a \lt 1</m>.
Denote by <m>C_a</m>, <m>C_b</m> the curves of parts (a) and (b),
respectively. Define <m>R</m> to be the set of points that are inside <m>C_b</m>
and outside <m>C_a</m>. That is,
<me>
R=\Set{(x,y)}{-1\le x \le 1,\ -1\le y\le 1,\ x^2+y^2\ge a^2 }
</me>
Then the boundary, <m>\partial R</m>, of <m>R</m> consists of two parts.
One part is <m>C_b</m>.
The other part is <m>C_a</m>, but oriented clockwise rather than
counterclockwise. We'll call it <m>-C_a</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="37%">
  <image source="pfigs/singGnC"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Again the partial derivatives
<m>\pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)</m>
and
<m>\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)</m>
are well-defined and equal everywhere in <m>R</m>. So by Green's theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{\partial R} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
&amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\dblInt_R\left[
   \pdiff{}{x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
 -\pdiff{}{y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)\right]\dee{x}\, \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
Consequently
<md>
<mrow>
0 &amp;= \frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{\partial R} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
= \frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{C_b} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
+ \frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{-C_a} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}

</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{C_b} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
- \frac{1}{2\pi}\oint_{C_a} \frac{x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}}{x^2+y^2}
</mrow>
</md>
and we conclude that the answers to parts (a) and (b) should be
the same.We did indeed see that in Q[<xref ref="prb_Green_singular"/>].
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup><introduction><procedural/></introduction>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate   <m>\int_C\vF\cdot d\vr</m> where
<m>\vF = x^2y^2\,\hi + 2xy\,\hj</m> and <m>C</m> is the boundary of the square in the
<m>xy</m>-plane having one vertex at the origin and diagonally opposite vertex at the point <m>(3, 3)</m>, oriented counterclockwise.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
For practice, evaluate this integral twice <mdash/> once directly and once
using Green's theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-54</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><title>Direct evaluation</title>
<p>
Here is a sketch of <m>C</m>.
</p>
<sidebyside width="30%">
<image source="pfigs/square3"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The square consists of four line segments.
<ul>
<li>
The bottom line segment may be parametrized
<m>\vr(x)=(x,0),\ 0\le x\le 3</m>. So the line integral along
this segment is
<me>
\int_0^3 \vF(\vr(x))\cdot\diff{\vr}{x}\ \dee{x}
=\int_0^3 (0, 0)\cdot(1, 0)\ \dee{x}
=0
</me>
</li>
<li>
The second line segment may be parametrized
<m>\vr(y)=(3,y),\ 0\le y\le 3</m>. So the line integral along
this segment is
<me>
\int_0^3 \vF(\vr(y))\cdot\diff{\vr}{y}\ \dee{y}
=\int_0^3 (9y^2, 6y)\cdot(0, 1)\ \dee{y}
=\int_0^3 6y\ \dee{y}
=27
</me>
</li>
<li>
The third line segment may be parametrized
<m>\vr(t)=(3-t,3),\ 0\le t\le 3</m>. So the line integral along
this segment is
<md>
<mrow>
\int_0^3 \vF(\vr(t))\cdot\diff{\vr}{t}\ \dee{t}
&amp;=\int_0^3 \big(9(3-t)^2\,,\, 6(3-t)\big)\cdot(-1\,,\,0)\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_0^3 9(3-t)^2\ \dee{t}
=-81
</mrow>
</md>
</li>
<li>
The final line segment may be parametrized
<m>\vr(t)=(0,3-t),\ 0\le t\le 3</m>. So the line integral along
this segment is
<me>
\int_0^3 \vF(\vr(t))\cdot\diff{\vr}{t}\ \dee{t}
=\int_0^3 (0, 0)\cdot(0, -1)\ \dee{t}
=0
</me>
</li>
</ul>
The full line integral is
<me>
\oint_C\vF\cdot d\vr=0+27-81+0=-54
</me>
</p>
</solution>

<solution><title>By Green's theorem</title>
<p>
 We apply Green's Theorem.
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C x^2y^2\,\dee{x}+2xy\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^3\dee{x}\int_0^3 \dee{y}\
            \left[\pdiff{}{x}(2xy)-\pdiff{}{y}(x^2y^2)\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^3\dee{x}\int_0^3 \dee{y}\ \big[2y-2x^2y\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^3\dee{x}\ \big[9-9x^2\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=27-9\frac{3^3}{3}=-54
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate
 <m>\ds\oint_C (x\sin y^2 -y^2)\,\dee{x}+(x^2y\cos y^2+3x)\,\dee{y}</m>
where <m>C</m> is the
counterclockwise boundary of the trapezoid with vertices <m>(0,-2),\ (1,-1),\
(1,1)</m> and <m>(0,2)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The <m>\sin y^2</m> and <m>\cos y^2</m> in the integrand look hard to integrate.
Try Green's theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>9</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Call the trapezoid <m>T</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="26%">
<image source="pfigs/trapGn"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
By Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\oint_C (x\sin y^2 -y^2)\,\dee{x}+(x^2y\cos y^2+3x)\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_T\left\{\pdiff{}{x}(x^2y\cos y^2+3x)
-\pdiff{}{y} (x\sin y^2 -y^2)\right\}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_T\big(2xy\cos y^2+3-2xy\cos y^2+2y\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_T\big(3+2y\big)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
The integral <m>\dblInt_T(2y)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m> vanishes because <m>2y</m> changes
sign under <m>y\rightarrow-y</m> while the domain of
integration is invariant under <m>y\rightarrow -y</m>.  The integral
<m>\dblInt_T 3\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m> is <m>3</m> times the area of the
trapezoid, which is its width (1) times the average of its heights
<m>(\half[2+4])=3</m>. So
<me>
\oint_C (x\sin y^2 -y^2)\,\dee{x}+(x^2y\cos y^2+3x)\,\dee{y}
               =3\times 1\times 3 = 9
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 1999A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 Evaluate
<m> I=
\ds\oint_{\cC} \Big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\Big)\,\dee{x}
+\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
</m>
counterclockwise around the boundary of the half-disk <m>0\le y\le \sqrt{4-x^2}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Don't do the integral directly.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{32}{3}\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><title>Using Green's theorem</title>
<p>
By Green's theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
using <m>D</m> to
denote the half-disk <m>0\le y\le \sqrt{4-x^2}</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\ds\oint_{\cC} \Big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\Big)\,\dee{x}
+\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in
=\dblInt_D\Big[\pdiff{}{x}\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)
-\pdiff{}{y}\Big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\Big) \Big] \dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_D\big(x^4+2x^2y^2+y^4\big)\ \dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_D\big(x^2+y^2\big)^2\ \dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Switching to polar coordinates
<md>
<mrow>
\ds\oint_{\cC} \Big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\Big)\,\dee{x}
+\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^2 dr\ r\int_0^{\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^4
={\pi\frac{r^6}{6}\bigg|}_0^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{32}{3}\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<solution><title>By direct evaluation</title>
<p>
Write <m>\cC</m> as the union of <m>\cC_1</m>, the straight line from
<m>(-2,0)</m> to <m>(2,0)</m>, and <m>\cC_2</m>, the half-circle <m>\vr(\theta)=x(\theta)\,\hi+y(\theta)\,\hj=2\cos\theta\,\hi+2\sin\theta\,\hj</m>,
<m>0\le\theta\le \pi</m>. As <m>y=0</m> at every point of <m>\cC_1</m>,
<m>\
\int_{\cC_1} \big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\big)\,\dee{x}
+\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)\,\dee{y}=0
\ </m> and
<md>
<mrow>
I&amp;=\int_{\cC_2} \Big(\frac{1}{3}x^2y^3-x^4y\Big)\,\dee{x}
+\big(xy^4+x^3y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^\pi\Big[ \Big(\frac{1}{3}x(\theta)^2y(\theta)^3-x(\theta)^4y(\theta)\Big)\,x'(\theta)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip2in
+\big(x(\theta)y(\theta)^4+x(\theta)^3y(\theta)^2\big)y'(\theta)\Big]
          \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^\pi\Big[ \Big(\frac{1}{3}2^5\cos^2\theta\sin^3\theta-2^5\cos^4\theta\sin\theta\Big)\,
                 (-2\sin\theta)
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
+\big(2^5\cos\theta\sin^4\theta+2^5\cos^3\theta\sin^2\theta\big)\,
               (2\cos\theta)\Big]\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2^5\int_0^\pi \Big(\frac{4}{3}\cos^2\theta\sin^4\theta+4\cos^4\theta\sin^2\theta\Big)
\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2^5\int_0^\pi \sin^2(2\theta)\big(\frac{1}{3}\sin^2\theta+\cos^2\theta\big)\,
\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2^4\int_0^\pi \sin^2(2\theta)\Big(\frac{1}{3}[1-\cos(2\theta)]+[1+\cos(2\theta)]\Big)\,
\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;\hskip2in\hbox{ since }\cos(2\theta)=2\cos^2\theta-1=1-2\sin^2\theta
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{2^5}{3}\int_0^\pi \sin^2(2\theta)\big[2+\cos(2\theta)\big]\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{2^5}{3}\int_0^\pi \big[1-\cos(4\theta)+\sin^2(2\theta)\cos(2\theta)\big]\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{2^5}{3} \Big[\theta-\frac{1}{4}\sin(4\theta)+\frac{1}{6}\sin^3(2\theta)\Big]_0^\pi
=\frac{32}{3}\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2018A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\cC</m> be the counterclockwise boundary of the rectangle
with vertices <m>(1,0)</m>, <m>(3,0)</m>, <m>(3,1)</m> and <m>(1,1)</m>. Evaluate
<me>
\oint_\cC\big(3y^2+2xe^{y^2}\big)\,\dee{x} + \big(2yx^2 e^{y^2}\big)\,\dee{y}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Don't do the integral directly. Sketch the rectangle.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-6</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Let's use Green's theorem. The
rectangle, which we shall denote <m>\cR</m>, is
</p>

<sidebyside widths="45% 51%" valign="middle">
  <p><m>\cR=\set{(x,y)}{1\le x\le 3,\ 0\le y\le 1}</m></p>
<image source="pfigs/domainPlgmB"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So Green's theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\oint_\cC\big(3y^2+2xe^{y^2}\big)\,\dee{x} + \big(2yx^2 e^{y^2}\big)\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_\cR \Big[
      \pdiff{}{x}\big(2yx^2 e^{y^2}\big)
     -\pdiff{}{y}\big(3y^2+2xe^{y^2}\big)
   \Big]\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=\dblInt_\cR \Big[
      4xy e^{y^2}
     -6y -4xye^{y^2}
   \Big]\,\dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in = -6 \int_1^3 \dee{x}\int_0^1 \dee{y}\ y
       = -6 \int_1^3 \dee{x}\ \frac{1}{2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in=-6
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the closed region enclosed by the curves
<m>y = x^2 + 4x + 4</m> and <m>y = 4 - x^2</m>. Let
<m>C</m> be its boundary and suppose that <m>C</m> is oriented counter-clockwise.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
   Draw the <em>oriented</em> curve <m>C</m> carefully in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
</li>
<li>
    Determine the value of
    <me>
         \oint_C xy\, \dee{x} + (e^y + x^2 ) \dee{y}
     </me>
</li>
</ol>
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Do not compute the integral directly.
</p></hint>

<answer>
<p>(a)</p>
<sidebyside width="57%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE16A_1a"/>
</sidebyside>
<p>
(b) <m>-\frac{8}{3}</m>
</p>
</answer>

<solution><p>  (a)
The curves <m>y = x^2 + 4x + 4</m> and <m>y = 4 - x^2</m> meet when
<me>
x^2 + 4x + 4 = 4 - x^2
\iff 2x^2  +4x = 2x(x+2) = 0
</me>
So the curves intersect at <m>(0,4)</m> and  <m>(-2,0)</m>. Here is a sketch.
</p>

<sidebyside width="57%">
<image source="pfigs/OE16A_1"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
 (b) Let
<me>
R=\Set{(x,y)\in\bbbr^2}{ x^2+4x+4\le y\le  4-x^2,\ -2\le x\le 0}
</me>
By Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>)
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C xy\, \dee{x} + (e^y + x^2 ) \dee{y}
&amp;=\dblInt_R \left\{
  \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x}(e^y+x^2)
  -\tfrac{\partial }{\partial y}(xy)
\right\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_{-2}^0\dee{x} \int_{x^2+4x+4}^{4-x^2}\dee{y} \ x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_{-2}^0\dee{x}\ (-2x^2-4x) x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\left[-\frac{x^4}{2} -\frac{4x^3}{3}\right]^0_{-2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\frac{8}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<me>
\vF(x, y) = \big(y^2 - e^{-y^2} + \sin x\,,\, 2xye^{-y^2} + x\big)
</me>
Let <m>C</m> be the boundary of the triangle with vertices <m>(0, 0)</m>, <m>(1, 0)</m> and
<m>(1, 2)</m>, oriented counter-clockwise. Compute
<me>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Don't do the integral directly. Sketch the triangle.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-\frac{1}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The integral that would be used for direct evaluation looks very
complicated. So let's try Green's theorem. The curve <m>C</m> is the
boundary of the triangle
</p>

<sidebyside widths="50% 30%" valign="middle">
<p><m>  T = \Set{(x,y)}{0\le x\le 1, 0\le y\le 2x}
</m></p>
<image source="pfigs/OE10D_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \int_C \big\{\big(y^2 - e^{-y^2} + \sin x\big)\dee{x}
               +\big(2xye^{-y^2} + x\big)\dee{y}\big\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_T \big\{
             \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x}\big(2xye^{-y^2} + x\big)
           -\tfrac{\partial }{\partial y}\big(y^2 - e^{-y^2} + \sin x\big)
               \big\}\dee{x}\dee{y} \hskip0.1in

</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_T \big\{
             \big(2ye^{-y^2} + 1\big)
           - \big(2y +2y e^{-y^2} \big)
               \big\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^{2x}\dee{y}\  \big\{1-2y\big\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_0^1\dee{x}\  \big\{2x-4x^2\big\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=1-\frac{4}{3} = -\frac{1}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2009A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Suppose the curve <m>C</m> is the boundary of the region enclosed between
the curves <m>y = x^2 - 4x+3</m> and <m>y = 3 - x^2 + 2x</m>. Determine the value
of the line integral
<me>
\int_C \big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2 + x^2}\big)\, \dee{x}
            + x^2 (2 + e^y)\, \dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is traversed counter-clockwise.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The integrand for direct evaluation looks complicated <mdash/>
don't evaluate this integral directly.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>54</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Here is a sketch of the two curves in question.
</p>

<sidebyside width="33%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE09A_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Note that the curves <m>y = x^2 - 4x+3</m> and <m>y = 3 - x^2 + 2x</m>
intersect when <m>x^2 - 4x+3 = 3 - x^2 + 2x</m> or <m>2x^2-6x=2x(x-3)=0</m> or
<m>x=0</m>, <m>3</m>.
</p>

<p>The integrand for direct evaluation looks complicated. So
let's use Green's theorem with
<m>F_1(x,y) = 2xe^y + \sqrt{2 + x^2}</m>, <m>F_2(x,y)= x^2 (2 + e^y)</m>
and
<me>
R=\Set{(x,y)}{x^2 - 4x+3 \le y\le 3 - x^2 + 2x,\ 0\le x\le 3}
</me>
By Green's theorem, which is Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2 + x^2}\big)\, \dee{x}
            + x^2 (2 + e^y)\, \dee{y}
&amp;=\dblInt_R\left\{\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
                 -\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\right\}\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_R\left\{2x(2+e^y) - 2xe^y\right\}\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=4 \int_0^3\dee{x} \int_{x^2 - 4x+3}^{3 - x^2 + 2x}\dee{y}\ x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=4 \int_0^3\dee{x}\ (6x-2x^2) x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=4\left[2x^3-\frac{1}{2}x^4\right]_0^3
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=54
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2006A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<md>
<mrow>
\vF(x,y) = \big(\tfrac{3}{2}y^2 + e^{-y} +\sin x\big)\,\hi
           +\big(\tfrac{1}{2}x^2+x-x e^{-y}\big)\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
Find <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>, where <m>C</m> is the boundary of the triangle
<m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(1,-2)</m>, <m>(1,2)</m>, oriented anticlockwise.
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Direct evaluation is not the most efficient method available.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{10}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Direct evaluation will lead to three integrals, one for each side of the
triangle. The integral from <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(1,-2)</m> and the integral from
<m>(1,2)</m> to <m>(0,0)</m> will each contain six (nonconstant) terms. This
does not look very efficient.
So let's try Green's theorem. Denote by <m>T</m>, the triangle
</p>


<sidebyside widths="50% 33%" valign="middle">
  <p><m>T = \Set{(x,y)}{0\le x\le 1,\ -2x\le y\le 2x}</m></p>
  <image source="pfigs/OE06A_4"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
It has boundary <m>\partial T=C</m>, oriented counterclockwise as desired.
So, by Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \int_{\partial T} \big\{\big(\tfrac{3}{2}y^2 + e^{-y} +\sin x\big)\dee{x}
               +\big(\tfrac{1}{2}x^2+x-x e^{-y}\big)\dee{y}\big\}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_T \big\{
    \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x}\big(\tfrac{1}{2}x^2+x-x e^{-y}\big)
   -\tfrac{\partial }{\partial y}\big(\tfrac{3}{2}y^2 + e^{-y} +\sin x\big)
               \big\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_T \big\{
             \big(x + 1-e^{-y}\big)
           - \big(3y - e^{-y} \big)
               \big\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \dblInt_T \big\{ x -3y + 1 \big\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Now
<md>
<mrow>
\dblInt_T  \dee{x}\dee{y} &amp;=\text{Area}(T) = \frac{1}{2}(4)(1) = 2
</mrow><mrow>
\dblInt_T  y\ \dee{x}\dee{y} &amp;= 0
   \qquad\text{since $y$ is odd under } y\rightarrow-y
</mrow><mrow>
\dblInt_T  x\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_{-2x}^{2x} \dee{y}\ x
 =\int_0^1 4x^2\ \dee{x}
 =\frac{4}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
So
<me>
\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = \frac{4}{3}-3\times 0 +2 =\frac{10}{3}
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2015A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Use Green's theorem to evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\dee{x} + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the arc of the parabola <m>y = \frac{1}{4}x^2 + 1</m> from
<m>(-2, 2)</m> to <m>(2, 2)</m>.
</li>
<li>
Use Green's theorem to evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\dee{x} + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the arc of the parabola <m>y = x^2 -2</m> from
<m>(-2, 2)</m> to <m>(2, 2)</m>.
</li>
<li>
Is the vector field
<me>
\vF=\frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\hi + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\hj
</me>
conservative? Provide a reason for your answer based on your answers
to the previous parts of this question.
</li>
</ol>
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Green's theorem must be applied to a closed curve; note that the
curve <m>C</m> is not closed.
</p>

<p>Consider carefully the point <m>(0, 0)</m> in your analysis.
</p>

<p>You may use the fact that
<m>\int \frac{\dee{t}}{1+t^2} = \arctan(t) + C</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>-\frac{\pi}{2}</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m></p><p>
(c) No.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Set
<me>
\vF=\frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\hi + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\hj
</me>
</p>

<p>(a) Green's theorem must be applied to a curve that is closed,
so that it is the boundary of a region in <m>\bbbr^2</m>. The given curve <m>C</m>
is not closed. But it is  part of the boundary of
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{-2\le x\le 2,\ \tfrac{x^2}{4}+1\le y\le 2}
</me>
Here is a sketch of <m>R</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="60%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE15A_3"/>
</sidebyside>
<p>
The boundary of <m>R</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> <m>C</m> on the bottom
and the line segment <m>L</m> from <m>(2,2)</m> to <m>(-2,2)</m> on the top.
Note that <m>\vF</m> is well-defined on all of <m>R</m> and that
<md>
<mrow>
\pdiff{}{x} \vF_2 -
\pdiff{}{y} \vF_1
&amp;=\pdiff{}{x} \frac{x}{x^2+y^2} +
\pdiff{}{y} \frac{y}{x^2+y^2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{(x^2+y^2) - x(2x)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
  +\frac{(x^2+y^2) - y(2y)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
on all of <m>R</m>. So, by Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\dee{x} + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\dee{y}
&amp;=\dblInt_R \Big(\pdiff{}{x} \vF_2 -
          \pdiff{}{y} \vF_1 \Big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
 - \int_L\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_{-L}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  =\int_{-2}^2 \vF_1\,\dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;
  =-\int_{-2}^2\frac{2}{x^2+4} \,\dee{x}\quad\text{since $y=2$ on $L$}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_{-1}^1\frac{4}{4u^2+4} \,\dee{x}
\quad\text{with } x=2u, \dee{x}=2\dee{u}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\arctan u\Big|_{-1}^1 =-\frac{\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
In the second line, we used the notation <m>-L</m> for the line segment
from <m>(-2,2)</m> to <m>(2,2)</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) This question looks a lot like that of part (a). But there is
a critical difference. Again <m>C</m> is not closed and again it is
part of the boundary of a simple region in the <m>xy</m>-plane, namely
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{-2\le x\le 2,\ x^2-2\le y\le 2}
</me>
This <m>R</m> is sketched below.
</p>
<sidebyside width="52%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE15A_3b1"/>
</sidebyside>
<p>
We <em>cannot</em> continue as in part (a), using this <m>R</m>, because
<m>\pdiff{}{x} \vF_2 -
\pdiff{}{y} \vF_1 </m> is <em>not</em> zero througout <m>R</m>.
In fact, it is <em>not</em> even defined throughout <m>R</m> <mdash/> it is not defined
at <m>(0,0)</m>, which is a point of <m>R</m>. We can work around this obstruction
by
<ul>
<li>
choosing a number <m>\rho \gt 0</m> that is small enough that the circle
<m>C_\rho</m> parametrized by
<me>
\vr(\theta) = \rho\cos\theta\,\hi +\rho\sin\theta\,\hj\qquad
0\le \theta \le 2\pi
</me>
is completely contained inside <m>R</m> (ror example, <m>\rho=1</m> is fine)
</li>
<li>
and then removing from <m>R</m> the interior of <m>C_\rho</m>.
</li>
</ul>
This produces the <q>deformed washer</q>
<me>
W = \Set{(x,y)}{-2\le x\le 2,\ x^2-2\le y\le 2,\ x^2+y^2\ge\rho^2}
</me>
that is sketched below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="52%">
 <image source="pfigs/OE15A_3b2"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The boundary of <m>W</m> consists the three parts <mdash/>
 the curve of interest <m>C</m> on the bottom,
 the line segment <m>L</m> from <m>(2,2)</m> to <m>(-2,2)</m> on the top,
 and the circle <m>-C_\rho</m> (that is <m>C_\rho</m> but oriented clockwise,
 rather than counter-clockwise) around the hole in the middle. Now
<m>\pdiff{}{x} \vF_2 -
\pdiff{}{y} \vF_1 </m>
is well-defined and zero throughout <m>W</m>. So, by Green's theorem
(Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\dee{x} + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\dblInt_W \Big(\pdiff{}{x} \vF_2 -
          \pdiff{}{y} \vF_1 \Big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
 - \int_L\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}- \int_{-C_\rho}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\int_{-L}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  + \int_{C_\rho}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
We have already found, in part (a), that
<m>\int_{-L}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=-\frac{\pi}{2}</m>. So it remains only to use
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(\theta) &amp;= \rho\cos\theta\,\hi +\rho\sin\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(\theta) &amp;= -\rho\sin\theta\,\hi +\rho\cos\theta\,\hj
</mrow>
</md>
to evaluate
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_\rho}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot\vr'(\theta)\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_0^{2\pi} \Big(\overbrace{-\frac{1}{\rho}\sin\theta\,\hi+\frac{1}{\rho}\cos\theta\,\hj}^
               {\vF(\vr(\theta))}\Big)
 \cdot\big(\overbrace{-\rho\sin\theta\,\hi +\rho\cos\theta\,\hj}^
                     {\vr'(\theta)}\big)\,\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
All together
<me>
\int_C \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\dee{x} + \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\dee{y}
=\int_{-L}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
  + \int_{C_\rho}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
=-\frac{\pi}{2} +2\pi
=\frac{3\pi}{2}
</me>
</p>

<p>(c) No, <m>\vF</m> is not conservative. We found, in parts (a) and (b),
two different values for the integrals along two paths, both of which start
at <m>(-2,2)</m> and end at <m>(2,2)</m>. So <m>\vF</m> does not have the
<q>path independence</q> property of Theorem <xref ref="thm_pathIndepConserv"/>.c
and cannot be conservative.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2012J</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Suppose the curve <m>C</m> is the boundary of the region enclosed between
the curves <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 3</m> and <m>y = 3 - x^2 + 2x</m>. Determine the
value of the line integral
<me>
\int_C \big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2} + x^2\big)\dee{x}
      + x^2 \big(2 + e^y)\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is traversed counter-clockwise.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
If we were to try to evaluate this integral directly, then on the
<m>y=x^2-4x+3</m> part of <m>C</m>, the
integrand would contain <m>x^2 e^y = x^2 e^{x^2-4x+3}</m>. That looks hard to integrate, so try Green's theorem.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>54</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The given integral is of the form <m>\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
with
<me>
\vF = \big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2} + x^2\big)\,\hi
      + x^2 \big(2 + e^y)\,\hj
</me>
If we were to try to evaluate this integral directly, then on the
<m>y=x^2-4x+3</m> part of <m>C</m>, the
integrand would contain <m>x^2 e^y = x^2 e^{x^2-4x+3}</m>. That looks hard to integrate, so let's try Green's theorem.
The parabolas <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 3</m> and <m>y = 3 - x^2 + 2x</m>
intersect at <m>(x,y)</m> with
<md>
<mrow>
x^2 - 4x + 3 = 3 - x^2 + 2x
&amp;\iff
2x^2 -6x = 0
\iff
2x(x-3)=0
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\iff
x=0\text{ or }x=3
</mrow>
</md>
The curve <m>C</m> is the boundary
of
<me>
R= \Set{(x,y)}{0\le x\le 3,\ x^2 - 4x + 3 \le y\le  3 - x^2 + 2x}
</me>
It is sketched below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="68%">
<image source="pfigs/OE12J_7"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
By Green's theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C \big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2} + x^2\big)\dee{x}
      + x^2 \big(2 + e^y)\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in
= \dblInt_R\Big[\pdiff{}{x}\big(x^2 \big(2 + e^y)\big)
-\pdiff{}{y}\big(2xe^y + \sqrt{2} + x^2\big)\Big] \dee{x}\dee{y}

</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in = \dblInt_R \big(2x(2+e^y) - 2xe^y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in =4 \int_0^3\dee{x}\int_{x^2 - 4x + 3}^{3 - x^2 + 2x}\dee{y}\  x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=4 \int_0^3\dee{x}\ x\big[(3 - x^2 + 2x) - (x^2 - 4x + 3)\big]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip1in =4 \int_0^3\dee{x}\ \big(6x^2-2x^3\big)
= 4\big(2\times 3^3-\frac{1}{2}3^4\big)
=54
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2016D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vF(x, y) = P \,\hi + Q\,\hj</m> be a smooth plane vector field
defined for <m>(x,y) \ne (0, 0)</m>, and suppose <m>Q_x = P_y</m> for
<m>(x,y) \ne  (0, 0)</m>. In the following <m>I_j = \int_{C_j} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
for integer <m>j</m>, and all <m>C_j</m> are positively oriented circles. Suppose
<m>I_1 = \pi</m> where <m>C_1</m> is the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Find <m>I_2</m> for <m>C_2 : (x - 2)^2 + y^2 = 1</m>. Explain briefly.
</li>
<li>
Find <m>I_3</m> for <m>C_3 : (x - 2)^2 + y^2 = 9</m>. Explain briefly.
</li>
<li>
Find <m>I_4</m> for <m>C_4 : (x - 2)^2 + (y-2)^2 = 9</m>. Explain briefly.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Beware the point <m>(0,0)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>I_2=0</m></p><p>
(b) <m>I_3=\pi</m></p><p>
(c) <m>I_4=\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) Denote by
<me>
R_2=\Set{(x,y)}{ (x-2)^2+y^2\le 1}
</me>
the interior of the circle <m>C_2</m>. Note that <m>(0,0)</m> is <em>not</em>
in <m>R_2</m>. Consequently, <m>Q_x-P_y=0</m> <em>everywhere</em> in <m>R_2</m> and,
by Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<me>
I_2 = \int_{C_2} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
    =\dblInt_{R_2} \big(Q_x-P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =0
</me>
</p>

<sidebyside widths="43% 43%" valign="middle">
<image source="pfigs/OE16D_4a"/>
<image source="pfigs/OE16D_4b"/>
</sidebyside>


<p>(b) We cannot blindly apply Green's theorem to <m>I_3=\int_{C_3}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
because <m>(0,0)</m> <em>is</em> in the interior of <m>C_3</m>, so that
<m>Q_x-P_y</m> is not identically zero in the interior of <m>C_3</m> <mdash/> it is not
even defined throughout the interior of <m>C_3</m>. We can work around this obstruction by considering the interior of <m>C_3</m> with the interior of <m>C_1</m>
removed. That is, by considering
<me>
R_3 = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2 + (y - 2)^2 \le 9,\ x^2+y^2\ge 1}
</me>
It is sketched on the right above.
The boundary of <m>R_3</m> consists of two parts
<ul>
<li>
the circle <m>C_3</m>, oriented counterclockwise, and
</li>
<li>
the circle <m>-C_1</m>. That is, the circle <m>C_1</m> but oriented clockwise,
rather than counterclockwise.
</li>
</ul>
Then <m>Q_x-P_y</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>R_3</m> and,
by Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
   0 &amp;=\dblInt_{R_3} \big(Q_x-P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
     = \int_{C_3} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             + \int_{-C_1} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{C_3} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             - \int_{C_1} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{C_3} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             - \pi
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>\int_{C_3} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = \pi</m>.
</p>

<p>(c) Again, we cannot blindly apply Green's theorem
to <m>I_4=\int_{C_4}\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
because <m>(0,0)</m> <em>is</em> in the interior of <m>C_4</m>. This time
we cannot remove the interior of <m>C_1</m> from the interior of <m>C_4</m>,
because <m>C_1</m> is not contained in the interior of <m>C_4</m>. Instead
we pick a number <m>\rho \gt 0</m> which is small enough that the
positively oriented circle
<me>
C_\rho = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2+y^2=\rho^2}
</me>
is completely inside <m>C_4</m>. Then we can define
<me>
R_4 = \Set{(x,y)}{(x-2)^2 + (y - 2)^2 \le 9,\ x^2+y^2\ge \rho^2}
</me>
It is sketched on the left below. We can now argue as in part (b).
The boundary of <m>R_4</m> consists of two parts
<ul>
<li>
the circle <m>C_4</m>, oriented counterclockwise, and
</li>
<li>
the circle <m>-C_\rho</m>. That is, the circle <m>C_\rho</m> but oriented clockwise,
rather than counterclockwise.
</li>
</ul>
Then <m>Q_x-P_y</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>R_4</m> and,
by Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
   0 &amp;=\dblInt_{R_4} \big(Q_x-P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{C_4} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             + \int_{-C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{C_4} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             - \int_{C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>\int_{C_4} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = \int_{C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>.
</p>

<p>To complete our computation, we have to determine
<m>\int_{C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>. We can do so by repeating the
same <q>removing a small disk containing <m>(0,0)</m></q> argument for the third time.
Set
<me>
R_5 = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2 + y^2 \le 1,\ x^2+y^2\ge \rho^2}
</me>
Then the boundary of <m>R_5</m> consists of <m>C_1</m> and <m>-C_\rho</m>,
and, as <m>Q_x-P_y</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>R_5</m>,
<md>
<mrow>
   0 &amp;=\dblInt_{R_5} \big(Q_x-P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{C_1} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             + \int_{-C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \pi
             - \int_{C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>\int_{C_4} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = \int_{C_\rho} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=\pi</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside widths="43% 43%" valign="middle">
  <image source="pfigs/OE16D_4c"/>
   <image source="pfigs/OE16D_4d"/>
</sidebyside>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Consider the vector field <m>\vF = P\,\hi + Q\,\hj</m>, where
<me>
P=\frac{x+y}{x^2+y^2},\qquad
Q=\frac{y-x}{x^2+y^2}
</me>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Compute and simplify <m>Q_x - P_y</m>.
</li>
<li>
Compute the integral <m>\int_{C_R} \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}</m>
directly using a parameterization, where <m>C_R</m> is the circle of radius <m>R</m>,
centered at the origin, and oriented in the counterclockwise direction.
</li>
<li>
Is <m>\vF</m> conservative? Carefully explain how your answer fits with the
results you got in the first two parts.
</li>
<li>
Use Green's theorem to compute <m>\int_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}</m> where <m>C</m>
is the triangle with vertices <m>(1, 1)</m>, <m>(1, 0)</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m> oriented in
the counterclockwise direction.
</li>
<li>
Use Green's theorem to compute <m>\int_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}</m> where <m>C</m>
is the triangle with vertices <m>(-1, -1)</m>, <m>(1, 0)</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m> oriented in
the counterclockwise direction.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>Q_x-P_y=0</m> except at <m>(0,0)</m> where it is not defined.
</p>

<p>(b) <m>-2\pi</m></p><p>
(c) No.</p><p>
(d) <m>0</m></p><p>
(e) <m>-2\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)  If <m>(x,y)\ne (0,0)</m>, we have
<md>
<mrow>
Q_x - P_y
&amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\Big(\frac{y-x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
-\pdiff{}{y}\Big(\frac{x+y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{-(x^2+y^2)-(y-x)(2x)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
      -\frac{(x^2+y^2)-(x+y)(2y)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) Parametrize <m>C_R</m> by
<me>
\vr(\theta) = R\cos\theta\,\hi +R\sin\theta\,\hj\qquad
0\le\theta\le 2\pi
</me>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{C_R} \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \overbrace{\frac{1}{R}
   \left\{\big(\cos\theta+\sin\theta\big)\hi
           +\big(\sin\theta-\cos\theta\big)\hj\right\}}^{\vF(\vr(\theta))}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip2in       \cdot
     \big(\overbrace{-R\sin\theta\,\hi+R\cos\theta\,\hj}^{\vr'(\theta)}\big)
           \,\dee{\theta}

</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}(-1)\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-2\pi
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(c) If <m>\vF</m> were conservative, the line integral <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m>
would be <m>0</m> for any closed curve <m>C</m>, by
Theorem <xref ref="thm_pathIndepConserv"/>.b.
So <m>\vF</m> is <em>not</em> conservative. Note that <m>\vF</m> is not defined at
<m>(x,y) = (0,0)</m> and so fails the screening
test <m>\vnabla\times\vF=\vZero</m> at <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>.
</p>

<p>(d) Denote by <m>\cR</m> the interior of the triangle <m>C</m>. It is the grey
region in the figure
</p>

<sidebyside width="37%">
<image source="pfigs/OE17A_6a"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Note that <m>(0,0)</m> is <em>not</em> in <m>\cR</m>. So <m>Q_x - P_y</m> is defined
and zero throughout <m>\cR</m>. So, by Green's theorem  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;= \dblInt_\cR\big(Q_x - P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
=0
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(e) Note that <m>(0,0)</m> <em>is</em> in the interior of triangle <m>C</m> specified
for this part. So <m>Q_x - P_y</m> is <em>not</em> defined in that interior
and we cannot apply Green's theorem precisely as we did in part (d).
We can work around this obstruction by
<ul>
<li>
picking a number <m>r \gt 0</m> that is small
enough that the circle <m>C_r</m>, of radius <m>r</m> centred on <m>(0,0)</m>,
is completely contained in the interior of the triangle <m>C</m>.
</li>
<li><p>
Then we work with
the region <m>\cR</m> defined by removing the interior of the circle <m>C_r</m>
from the interior of the triangle <m>C</m>. It is the grey region sketched below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="53%">
<image source="pfigs/OE17A_6b"/>
</sidebyside>

</li>
</ul>
The boundary of <m>\cR</m> consists of two parts
<ul>
<li>
the triangle <m>C</m>, oriented counterclockwise, and
</li>
<li>
the circle <m>-C_r</m>. That is, the circle <m>C_r</m>, but oriented clockwise,
rather than counterclockwise.
</li>
</ul>
Then <m>Q_x-P_y</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>\cR</m> and,
by Green's theorem,
<md>
<mrow>
   0 &amp;=\dblInt_\cR \big(Q_x-P_y\big)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             + \int_{-C_r} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
             - \int_{C_r} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = \int_{C_r} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} </m>.
By part (b), with <m>R=r</m>, <m>\int_{C_r} \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=-2\pi</m>, so
<m>\int_C \vF\cdot\dee{\vr} = -2\pi</m>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Evaluate
<me>
\int_C \sqrt{1+x^3}\,\dee{x} +\big(2xy^2 + y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the unit circle <m>x^2+y^2 = 1</m>, oriented counterclockwise.
</li>
<li>
Evaluate
<me>
\int_C \sqrt{1+x^3}\,\dee{x} +\big(2xy^2 + y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is now the part of the unit circle <m>x^2+y^2 = 1</m>, with <m>x\ge 0</m>,
still oriented counterclockwise.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{\pi}{4}+\frac{2}{3}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a) The given integral is of the form
  <m>\int_C F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x}+F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}</m> with
<me>
F_1(x,y) = \sqrt{1+x^3}\qquad
F_2(x,y) = 2xy^2 + y^2\qquad
\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y} = 2y^2
</me>
As <m>C</m> is <m>\partial R</m> with
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{ x^2+y^2\le 1}
</me>
Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>)
gives
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \sqrt{1+x^3}\,\dee{x} +\big(2xy^2 + y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
&amp; = \int_C F_1(x,y)\,\dee{x}+F_2(x,y)\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;  = \dblInt_R \Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
           - \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 2 \dblInt_R y^2\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
Switching to polar coordinates
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \sqrt{1+x^3}\,\dee{x} +\big(2xy^2 + y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
&amp;= 2\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \int_0^1\dee{r}\
         r\big(r\sin\theta\big)^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= 2\left[\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2\theta\right]
   \left[\int_0^1\dee{r}\ r^3\right]
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=2\ \pi\ \frac{1}{4}
=\frac{\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
To do the <m>\theta</m> integral, we have used
<md>
<mrow>
\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2 \theta\ \dee{\theta}
=\int_0^{2\pi} \Big(\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\Big)\,\dee{\theta}
=\Big[\frac{\theta-\sin(2\theta)/2}{2} \Big]_0^{2\pi}
= \pi
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2 \theta\ \dee{\theta}</m>, see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p>

<p>(b) It is again natural to use Green's theorem.
But Green's theorem must be applied to a curve that is closed,
so that it is the boundary of a region in <m>\bbbr^2</m>. The given curve <m>C</m>
is not closed. But it is  part of the boundary of
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2+y^2\le 1,\ x\ge 0}
</me>
Here is a sketch of <m>R</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="40%">
 <image source="pfigs/OE17D_7"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
The boundary of <m>R</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> <m>C</m> on the right
and the line segment <m>L</m> from <m>(0,1)</m> to <m>(0,-1)</m> on the left.
Note that <m>\vF=F_1\,\hi +F_2\,\hj</m> is well-defined on all of <m>R</m>
and that we still have, from part (a),
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}  -
\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}
&amp;=2y^2
</mrow>
</md>
on all of <m>R</m>. So, by Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \sqrt{1+x^3}\,\dee{x} +\big(2xy^2 + y^2\big)\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\dblInt_R \Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x} -
          \frac{\partial F_2}{\partial y} \Big)\dee{x}\dee{y}
 - \int_L\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{\Atop{x^2+y^2\le 1}{x\ge 0}} 2y^2\  \dee{x}\dee{y}
  + \int_{-L} F_2\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_{x^2+y^2\le 1} y^2\  \dee{x}\dee{y}
  + \int_{-1}^1 y^2\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in\text{by symmetry for the first integral and}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in\text{since $x=0$ and $\dee{x}=0$ in the}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in\text{second integral}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{2}{3}
</mrow>
</md>
In the second line, we used the notation <m>-L</m> for the line segment
from <m>(0,-1)</m> to <m>(0,1)</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>
</exercisegroup>

