<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Evaluate the line integral
<me>
\int_C (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\dee{x} + (x \cos y + e^x ) \,\dee{y}
</me>
where <m>C</m> is the arc of the curve <m>x = \cos y</m> for <m>-\pi/2 \le y \le \pi/2</m>,
traversed in the direction of increasing <m>y</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
It is possible to evaluate this integral by three different methods,
one of them being direct evaluation (though it requires
some ingenuity). Try to find all three.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
First, here is a sketch of the curve <m>C</m>.
</p>
<sidebyside width="27%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE07A_6"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
We'll evaluate this integral in three different ways.
<ol marker="(1)">
<li><p> <em>Direct evaluation:</em> To evaluate the integral directly,
we'll parametrize <m>C</m> using <m>y</m> as the parameter. That is, we'll make <m>y(t)=t</m>:
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(t) &amp;= x(t)\,\hi+y(t)\,\hj
        = \cos t\,\hi + t\,\hj\qquad -\frac{\pi}{2}\le t\le\frac{\pi}{2}
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(t) &amp;= x'(t)\,\hi+y'(t)\,\hj
        = -\sin t\,\hi + \hj
</mrow>
</md>
So the integral is
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\dee{x} + (x \cos y + e^x ) \,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\Big\{ \big[x(t)^2 +y(t) e^{x(t)}\big]\diff{x}{t}(t)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip2in     +  \big[x(t) \cos(y(t)) + e^{x(t)}\big]\diff{y}{t}(t)
                        \Big\}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\Big\{ -\big[\cos^2 t + t e^{\cos t}\big]\sin t
                           +  \big[\cos^2 t + e^{\cos t}\big]
                        \Big\}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\Big\{ -\cos^2 t\sin t +\cos^2 t
                      - t e^{\cos t}\sin t + e^{\cos t}
                        \Big\}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\Big\{ \cos^2 t
                  +\diff{ }{t}\Big[\frac{\cos^3 t}{3} +te^{\cos t}\Big]
                        \Big\}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\Big\{ \frac{\cos(2t)+1}{2}
                  +\diff{ }{t}\Big[\frac{\cos^3 t}{3} +te^{\cos t}\Big]
                        \Big\}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\Big[ \frac{\sin(2t)}{4} +\frac{t}{2}+
                  \frac{\cos^3 t}{3} +te^{\cos t}
                        \Big]_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
  =\frac{3\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos^2 t\ \dee{t}</m> see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p></li>
<li><p> <em>Green's (or Stokes') theorem:</em>
The curve <m>C</m> is not closed so we cannot apply Green's theorem directly.
However the boundary of the region
<me>
R = \Set{(x,y)}{ 0\le x\le\cos y,\
           -\frac{\pi}{2}\le y\le \frac{\pi}{2} }
</me>
(sketched below) consists of two parts, one of which is <m>C</m>. The other
is the line <m>L</m> from <m>\big(0,\frac{\pi}{2}\big)</m>
to <m>\big(0,-\frac{\pi}{2}\big)</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="28%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE07A_6b"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So Green's theorem gives
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\int_C (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\dee{x} + (x \cos y + e^x ) \,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\dblInt_R \Big\{\pdiff{}{x}(x \cos y + e^x )
          -\pdiff{}{y}(x^2 + y e^x )\Big\}\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in
-\int_L (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\dee{x} + (x \cos y + e^x ) \,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\dblInt_R \cos y\ \dee{x}\dee{y}  -  \int_L \,\dee{y}\qquad
    \text{since $x=0$ and $\dee{x}=0$ on } L
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\dee{y}\int_0^{\cos y}\dee{x}\ \cos y
                       -\int_{\pi/2}^{-\pi/2}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in=\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}\dee{y}\ \cos^2 y
                       + \pi
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in
  =\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{\cos(2y)+1}{2}\ \dee{y} + \pi
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in
  =\Big[ \frac{\sin(2y)}{4} +\frac{y}{2}\Big]_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} +\pi
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in
  =\frac{3\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md></p>
</li>
<li><p> <em>(Sort of) conservative fields:</em> The given integral
is <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> with
<m>\vF = (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\hi + (x \cos y + e^x ) \,\hj</m>. The curl of this
field is
<md>
<mrow>
\vnabla\times\vF
&amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
\hi &amp;\hj &amp;\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
</mrow><mrow>
x^2 + y e^x &amp; x \cos y + e^x &amp; 0
\end{matrix}
\right]
=\cos y\,\hk
</mrow>
</md>
So <m>\vF</m> violates our screening test and consequently is not conservative.
But it violates the screening test only because of the term <m>x\cos y\,\hj</m>.
This suggests that we split up
<me>
\vF = \vG +\vH\qquad\text{with}\quad
\vG= (x^2 + y e^x ) \,\hi + e^x \,\hj,\quad
\vH = x\cos y\,\hj
</me>
Then <m>\vG</m> is conservative with potential <m>g=\frac{x^3}{3}+ye^x</m>
and <m>\vH</m> is pretty simple, so that it is not hard to evaluate
<m>\int_C\vH\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> directly. Using the parametrization
<m>\vr(t) = \cos t\,\hi + t\,\hj</m>,  <m>-\frac{\pi}{2}\le t\le\frac{\pi}{2}</m>
as above,
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \int_C\vG\cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_C\vH\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;= \int_C\vnabla g\cdot\dee{\vr} + \int_C\vH\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=g\big(\vr(\frac{\pi}{2})\big) -g\big(\vr(-\frac{\pi}{2})\big)
   + \int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} x(t) \cos(y(t)) \diff{y}{t}(t)\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp; =g\big(0,\frac{\pi}{2}\big) -g\big(0,-\frac{\pi}{2}\big)
   +\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \cos^2 t \,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{\pi}{2} -\Big(-\frac{\pi}{2}\Big)
   +\int_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2} \frac{\cos(2t)+1}{2} \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\pi  + \Big[ \frac{\sin(2t)}{4} +\frac{t}{2}\Big]_{-\pi/2}^{\pi/2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{3\pi}{2}
</mrow>
</md></p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
 Use Green's theorem to establish that if <m>C</m> is a simple
closed curve in the plane, then the area <m>A</m> enclosed by <m>C</m> is given by
<me>
A=\frac{1}{2}\oint_C x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}
</me>
Use this to calculate the area inside the curve
<m>x^{2/3}+y^{2/3}=1</m>.
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
<m>\frac{3\pi}{8}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Call the region enclosed by the curve <m>R</m>. By Green's theorem,
Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>,
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{1}{2}\oint_C x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}
&amp;=\frac{1}{2}\dblInt_R\Big(\pdiff{}{x}x
-\pdiff{}{y}(-y)\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
=\frac{1}{2}\dblInt_R 2\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=A
</mrow>
</md>
as desired. The curve <m>x^{2/3}+y^{2/3}=1</m> may be parametrized in the
counterclockwise orientation by <m>x(\theta)=\cos^3\theta</m>, <m>y(\theta)=\sin^3\theta</m>,
<m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
A&amp;=\frac{1}{2}\oint_C x\,\dee{y}-y\,\dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{2}\int_0^{2\pi}\big( x(\theta)y'(\theta)-y(\theta)x'(\theta)\big)\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{2}\int_0^{2\pi}\big( 3\cos^4\theta\sin^2\theta+3\sin^4\theta\cos^2\theta\big)\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{3}{2}\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
=\frac{3}{8}\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2(2\theta)\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{3}{16}\int_0^{2\pi}\big(1-\cos(4\theta)\big)\ \dee{\theta}
=\frac{3}{16}\Big[\theta-\frac{1}{4}\sin(4\theta)\Big]_0^{2\pi}
=\frac{3\pi}{8}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\vF(x,y)=(x+3y)\,\hi+(x+y)\,\hj</m> and
<m>\vG(x,y)=(x+y)\,\hi+(2x-3y)\,\hj</m> be vector fields. Find a number <m>A</m> such
that for each circle <m>C</m> in the plane
<me>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=A\oint_C\vG\cdot \dee{\vr}
</me>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Write <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}-A\oint_C\vG\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\oint_C(\vF-A\vG)\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>A=-2</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
If we use <m>D</m> to denote the disk inside the circle <m>C</m>
then we want
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}-A\oint_C\vG\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\oint_C(\vF-A\vG)\cdot \dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_D \Big[\pdiff{}{x}(\vF-A\vG)_2
-\pdiff{}{y}(\vF-A\vG)_1\Big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
to vanish for all disks <m>D</m>. We used Green's theorem, which is Theorem
<xref ref="thm_Green"/>,  in the last step.
This is the case if and only if
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\pdiff{}{x}(\vF-A\vG)_2
=\pdiff{}{y}(\vF-A\vG)_1
</mrow><mrow>
\iff&amp;
\pdiff{}{x}[(x+y)-A(2x-3y)]
=\pdiff{}{y}[(x+3y)-A(x+y)]
</mrow><mrow>
\iff&amp;
1-2A=3-A
</mrow><mrow>
\iff&amp; A=-2
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let
<m>\vF(x,y) = \frac{y^3}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}\hi
              -\frac{xy^2}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}\hj</m>, <m>(x,y)\ne (0,0)</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Compute <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m> where <m>C</m> is the unit circle
in the <m>xy</m>-plane, positively oriented.
</li>
<li>
Use (a) and Green's theorem to find <m>\oint_{C_0}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>
where <m>C_0</m> is the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{16}+\frac{y^2}{25}=1</m>, positively
oriented.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Note that <m>\vF(x,y)</m> is not defined at <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>-\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Parametrize the circle <m>\vr(\theta)=(\cos\theta,\sin\theta)</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)
&amp;=\sin^3\theta\,\hi -\cos\theta \sin^2\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\diff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta)&amp;=-\sin\theta\,\hi+\cos\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot \diff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta)
&amp;=-\sin^4\theta-\cos^2\theta\sin^2\theta=-\sin^2\theta
</mrow><mrow>
\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot \diff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta)\ \dee{\theta}
=-\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=-{\Big[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\Big]}_0^{2\pi}
=-\pi
</mrow>
</md>
For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
<m>\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}</m> see Example
<xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p>

<p>(b) Denote by <m>W</m> the washer shaped region between the circle
<m>x^2+y^2=1</m> and the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{16}+\frac{y^2}{25}=1</m>.
It is sketched below. By Green's theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_{C_0}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}-\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_W \Big[\pdiff{}{x}\vF_2
-\pdiff{}{y}\vF_1\Big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
For the specified <m>\vF</m>
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\pdiff{}{x}\vF_2
-\pdiff{}{y}\vF_1
=-\pdiff{}{x}\frac{xy^2}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}
-\pdiff{}{y}\frac{y^3}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=-\frac{y^2}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}+2\frac{xy^2(2x)}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^3}
-\frac{3y^2}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^2}+2\frac{y^3(2y)}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^3}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=\frac{-y^2(x^2+y^2)+4x^2y^2-3y^2(x^2+y^2)+4y^4}{ {(x^2+y^2)}^3}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.5in=0
</mrow>
</md>
Consequently
<me>
\oint_{C_0}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}-\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0
\implies
\oint_{C_0}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=\oint_C\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=-\pi
</me>
</p>

<sidebyside width="30%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE01DQ6"/>
</sidebyside>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2001A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\cC_1</m> be the circle <m>(x-2)^2+y^2=1</m> and let <m>\cC_2</m> be
the circle <m>(x-2)^2+y^2=9</m>. Let
<m>\vF=-\frac{y}{x^2+y^2}\,\hi+\frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\,\hj</m>. Find the integrals
<m>\oint_{\cC_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m> and <m>\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Note that <m>\vF(x,y)</m> is not defined at <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\oint_{\cC_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m> and <m>\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=2\pi</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
Observe that
<md>
<mrow>
\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}
-\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}
&amp;=\frac{\partial  }{\partial x}\Big( \frac{x}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
-\frac{\partial  }{\partial y}\Big( \frac{-y}{x^2+y^2}\Big)
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{(x^2+y^2)-x(2x)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}
+\frac{(x^2+y^2)-y(2y)}{{(x^2+y^2)}^2}=0
</mrow>
</md>
except at <m>(0,0)</m>, where <m>\vF</m> is not defined. Hence by Green's theorem
(Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<m>\oint_{\cC}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m> for any closed curve that does not contain
<m>(0,0)</m> in its interior.
In particular, <m>\oint_{\cC_1}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>. On the other hand,
<m>(0,0)</m> is contained in the interior of <m>\cC_2</m>, so we cannot use
Green's theorem to conclude that <m>\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=0</m>.
</p>

<p>Let <m>\cC_3</m> be the circle of radius one centred on <m>(0,0)</m> and
denote by <m>W</m> the washer shaped region between the circle
<m>\cC_2</m> and the circle <m>\cC_3</m>. It is sketched below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="43%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE01AQ5"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
By Green's theorem (Theorem <xref ref="thm_Green"/>),
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}-\oint_{\cC_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\dblInt_W \Big[\pdiff{}{x}\vF_2
-\pdiff{}{y}\vF_1\Big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
=0
</mrow>
</md>
So
<m>\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}=\oint_{\cC_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>. Parameterize
<m>\cC_3</m> by <m>x=\cos\theta</m>, <m>y=\sin\theta</m>. Then
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(\theta)&amp;=\cos\theta\,\hi+\sin\theta\,\hj\qquad 0\le \theta\le 2\pi
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(\theta)&amp;=-\sin\theta\,\hi+\cos\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)&amp;=-\sin\theta\,\hi+\cos\theta\,\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\vF\big(\vr(\theta)\big)\cdot\vr'(\theta)
&amp;=1
</mrow>
</md>
so that
<me>
\oint_{\cC_2}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\oint_{\cC_3}\vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
=\int_0^{2\pi} \dee{\theta}\ 1
=2\pi
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2000A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>R</m> be the region in the first quadrant of the <m>xy</m>-plane
bounded by the coordinate axes and the curve <m>y=1-x^2</m>. Let <m>\cC</m> be the
boundary of <m>R</m>, oriented counterclockwise.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Evaluate <m>\int_\cC x\,\dee{s}</m>.
</li>
<li>
 Evaluate <m>\int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}</m>, where <m>\vF(x,y)
=\big(\sin(x^2)-xy\big)\,\hi+\big(x^2+\cos(y^2)\big)\,\hj</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{12}\big[5^{3/2}-1\big]\approx 1.3484</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Let <m>\cC_1</m> be the line segment from <m>(0,1)</m> to <m>(0,0)</m>,
<m>\cC_2</m> be the line segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(1,0)</m> and
<m>\cC_3</m> be the curve <m>y=1-x^2</m> from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(0,1)</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="26%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE00AQ3"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Then
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{\cC_1} x\,\dee{s}&amp;=\int_{\cC_1} 0\,\dee{s}=0
</mrow><mrow>
\int_{\cC_2} x\,\dee{s}&amp;=\int_0^1 x\,\dee{x}=\frac{1}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
On <m>\cC_3</m>, <m>y=1-x^2</m> so that <m>\diff{y}{x}=-2x</m> and
<me>
\dee{s} =\sqrt{\dee{x}^2+\dee{y}^2}
        =\sqrt{1+\Big(\diff{y}{x}\Big)^2}\,\dee{x}
        =\sqrt{1+4x^2}\,\dee{x}
</me>
and
<md>
<mrow>
\int_{\cC_3} x\,\dee{s}
&amp;
=\int_0^1 x\sqrt{1+4x^2}\,\dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\Big[\frac{1}{12}(1+4x^2)^{3/2}\Big]_0^1
=\frac{1}{12}\big[5^{3/2}-1\big]
</mrow>
</md>
All together
<me>
\int_{\cC} x\,\dee{s}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{12}\big[5^{3/2}-1\big]
\approx 1.3484
</me>
</p>

<p>(b) By either Stokes' theorem or Green's theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\int_\cC \vF\cdot \dee{\vr}
&amp;=\dblInt_R\Big[\pdiff{}{x}\big(x^2+\cos(y^2)\big)
-\pdiff{}{y}\big(\sin(x^2)-xy\big) \Big]\ \dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_R3x\ \dee{x} \dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\int_0^1 \dee{x}\int_0^{1-x^2}\dee{y}\ x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\int_0^1 \dee{x}\ (1-x^2) x
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=3\Big[\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{4}\Big]=\frac{3}{4}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2010A</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
Let <m>C</m> be the curve defined by the intersection of the surfaces
<m>z = x + y</m> and <m>z = x^2 + y^2</m>.
<ol marker="a">
<li>
Show that <m>C</m> is a simple closed curve.
</li>
<li>
<p>
Evaluate <m>\oint_C \vF \cdot \dee{\vr}</m> where
<ol marker="(i)">
<li>
 <m>\vF = x^2\,\hi + y^2\,\hj + 3 e^z\,\hk</m>.
</li>
<li>
  <m>\vF = y^2\,\hi + x^2\,\hj + 3 e^z\,\hk</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
(a) All points on the curve obey an equation that contains <m>x</m>'s and <m>y</m>'s,
but no <m>z</m>'s.
</p>

<p>(b) Exploit conservativeness as much as possible.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) The projection of the curve on the <m>xy</m>-plane (i.e. the top view of the curve) is a circle. See the solution for more details.
</p>

<p>(b) (i) <m>0</m></p><p>
(b) (ii) <m>0</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p> (a)
If <m>(x,y,z)</m> is on the curve, it must obey both <m>z=x+y</m>
and <m>z=x^2+y^2</m> and hence it must also obey <m>x^2+y^2=x+y</m>
or <m>(x-\frac{1}{2})^2 + (y-\frac{1}{2})^2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>.
That's a circle. We can parametrize the curve by
<md>
<mrow>
x(\theta)&amp;= \frac{1}{2} +\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta
</mrow><mrow>
y(\theta)&amp;= \frac{1}{2} +\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta
</mrow><mrow>
z(\theta)&amp;= x+y = 1+ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\big[\cos\theta+\sin\theta\big]
</mrow>
</md>
with <m>0\le\theta \lt 2\pi</m>. As <m>\theta</m> runs from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>,
<m>\big(x(\theta),y(\theta)\big)</m> runs once around the circle without
crossing itself so that  <m>\big(x(\theta),y(\theta),z(\theta)\big)</m> runs
once around the curve without crossing itself. As
<m>\big(x(2\pi),y(2\pi),z(2\pi)\big)=\big(x(0),y(0),z(0)\big)</m>,
<m>C</m> is a simple closed curve.
</p>

<p> (b) (i) The vector field <m>\vF= x^2\,\hi + y^2\,\hj + 3 e^z\,\hk</m>
is conservative (with potential <m>\frac{1}{3}x^3 +\frac{1}{3}y^3 + 3e^z</m>).
So <m>\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=0</m>.
</p>

<p> (b) (ii) Note that the question did not specify the orientation
of <m>C</m>. It should have. We'll stick with the most commonly used orientation <mdash/>
counterclockwise when viewed from high on the <m>z</m>-axis.
The vector field <m>\vG= 3 e^z\,\hk</m>
is conservative (with potential <m>3e^z</m>).
So <m>\oint_C\vG\cdot\dee{\vr}=0</m> and, using the parametrization
<md>
<mrow>
\vr(\theta) &amp;= \Big[\frac{1}{2}\!+\!\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta\Big]\hi
             +\Big[\frac{1}{2}\! +\!\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta\Big]\hj
             +\Big[1 \!+\!\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta
                     \!+\!\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta\Big]\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vr'(\theta) &amp;= -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta\,\hi
                +\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta\,\hj
             +\Big[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta
                     -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta\Big]\hk
</mrow>
</md>
of part (a), we have
<md>
<mrow>
&amp;\oint_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
= \oint_C(\vF-\vG)\cdot\dee{\vr}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in= \int_0^{2\pi} \big[y(\theta)^2x'(\theta) +x(\theta)^2y'(\theta)\big]
           \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;\hskip0.25in= \int_0^{2\pi} \Big\{-\Big[\frac{1}{2} +\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta\Big]^2
                               \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sin\theta
                       +\Big[\frac{1}{2} +\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta\Big]^2
                               \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\cos\theta\Big\}
           \dee{\theta}
</mrow>
</md>
Because the integral of any odd power of <m>\sin\theta</m> or <m>\cos\theta</m>
over <m>0\le\theta\le 2\pi</m> is zero (see Example <xref ref="eg_stokesD"/>
in the  text),
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_c\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}
&amp;= \int_0^{2\pi} \Big\{-\frac{1}{2} \sin^2\theta
                       +\frac{1}{2} \cos^2\theta\Big\}
           \dee{\theta}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
since  (see Example <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/> in the  text)
<me>
\int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
=\int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
=\pi
</me>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
 Find a smooth, simple, closed,
counterclockwise oriented curve, <m>C</m>, in the <m>xy</m>-plane for the which
the value of the line integral
 <m>\oint_C(y^3-y)\,\dee{x}-2x^3\,dy</m> is a maximum among all
smooth, simple, closed, counterclockwise oriented curves.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Use Green's theorem to convert the integral over <m>C</m> into an integral
over the region <m>R</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane whose boundary is <m>C</m>. Consider
the sign of the integrand of the integral over <m>R</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>6x^2+3y^2= 1</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
By Green's Theorem
<md>
<mrow>
\oint_C(y^3-y)\,\dee{x}-2x^3\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\dblInt_R\Big[\pdiff{}{x}(-2x^3)
-\pdiff{}{y}(y^3-y)\Big]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\dblInt_R\Big[1-6x^2-3y^2\Big]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
</mrow>
</md>
where <m>R</m> is the region in the <m>xy</m>-plane whose boundary is <m>C</m>. Observe
that the integrand <m>1-6x^2-3y^2</m> is positive in the elliptical region
 <m>6x^2+3y^2\le 1</m> and negative outside of it. To maximize the integral
<m>\dblInt_R\big[1-6x^2-3y^2\big]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m> we should choose <m>R</m> to contain
all points <m>(x,y)</m> with the integrand <m>1-6x^2-3y^2\ge 0</m> and to exclude
all points <m>(x,y)</m> with the integrand <m>1-6x^2-3y^2 \lt  0</m>. So we
choose
<me>
R=\Set{(x,y)}{6x^2+3y^2\le 1}
</me>
The corresponding <m>C</m> is <m>6x^2+3y^2= 1</m>.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise></exercisegroup>

